.TH FRENAME 1 "June 2026" "frename 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
frename \- rename files in bulk via a user-provided naming standard
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B frename
.RB [ \-d
.IR directory ]
.RB [ \-s
.IR standard ]
.RB [ \-l
.IR delimiter ]
.RB [ \-r ]
.RB [ \-h ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B frename
scans a directory for files matching a naming standard, finds gaps in the
numeric sequence, and renames files to fill those gaps before extending
the sequence.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-d " " \fIdirectory\fR
Target directory to scan.
.TP
.BR \-s " " \fIstandard\fR
Base filename standard to match (e.g. \fIimg\fR for files like \fIimg_1.jpg\fR).
.TP
.BR \-l " " \fIdelimiter\fR
Delimiter separating the standard from the index. Default: \fI_\fR.
.TP
.B \-r
Preview changes without renaming any files.
.TP
.B \-h
Show usage information.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
frename \-d ./photos \-s img \-l _
Directory \fI./photos\fR contains \fIimg_1.jpg\fR, \fIimg_3.jpg\fR,
\fIvacation.jpg\fR, \fIscreenshot.png\fR. The first two already match the
standard and are left untouched. The other two don't match it, so they
are renamed to fill the gap and extend the sequence, becoming
\fIimg_2.jpg\fR and \fIimg_4.jpg\fR.
.TP
frename \-d ./photos \-s img \-r
Preview without applying changes.
